#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-ebms-partition.md:10
msgid "3.2 The Intractable Partition Function Problem"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-ebms-partition.md:12
msgid ""
"Section [3.1 Defining the Objective: Low Energy for Real Data](/kpp-"
"theoretical-foundations\\kpp-theoretical-foundations-ebms-def) introduced"
" the maximum likelihood objective for energy-based models and revealed "
"that the gradient of the negative log-likelihood contains a term "
"involving an expectation under the model distribution. This expectation, "
"in turn, requires summing over all possible configurations, a sum that is"
" encoded in the <b>partition function</b> $Z_\\theta$. In this section, "
"we examine why the partition function is computationally intractable, "
"what consequences this intractability has for learning and inference, and"
" why it constitutes the central algorithmic challenge for Boltzmann "
"machines and energy-based models more broadly."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-ebms-partition.md:14
msgid "<b>The Partition Function: Definition and Its Implications</b>"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-ebms-partition.md:16
#, python-brace-format
msgid ""
"Recall the definition of the partition function for a Boltzmann machine "
"with binary units $\\mathbf{x} \\in \\{0,1\\}^N$:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-ebms-partition.md:18
msgid ""
"Z_\\theta = \\sum_{\\tilde{\\mathbf{x}} \\in \\{0,1\\}^N} "
"\\exp\\left(-E_\\theta(\\tilde{\\mathbf{x}})\\right)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-ebms-partition.md:20
msgid ""
"The sum runs over <b>all </b>$2^N$<b> possible binary vectors</b> of "
"length $N$. For a modest network of $N=100$ visible units (a tiny image "
"by modern standards, only $10 \\times 10$ pixels), the number of terms in"
" this sum is:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-ebms-partition.md:22
#, python-brace-format
msgid "2^{100} \\approx 1.27 \\times 10^{30}"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-ebms-partition.md:24
msgid "To put this number in perspective:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-ebms-partition.md:26
#, python-brace-format
msgid ""
"The estimated number of stars in the observable universe is about "
"$10^{22}$ to $10^{24}$."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-ebms-partition.md:27
#, python-brace-format
msgid "The age of the universe is approximately $4.35 \\times 10^{17}$ seconds."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-ebms-partition.md:28
#, python-brace-format
msgid ""
"Even if we could evaluate one trillion ($10^{12}$) configurations per "
"second, enumerating $2^{100}$ configurations would take over "
"$10^{10}$times the age of the universe."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-ebms-partition.md:30
msgid ""
"And $N = 100$ is <b>tiny</b>. Real-world Boltzmann machines and "
"restricted Boltzmann machines often have hundreds of visible units and "
"hundreds or thousands of hidden units, yielding state spaces of size "
"$2^{N_{\\text{vis}} + N_{\\text{hid}}}$. The partition function is "
"<b>exponentially large</b> in the number of units."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-ebms-partition.md:32
msgid "<b>Why the Partition Function Matters</b>"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-ebms-partition.md:34
msgid "The partition function appears in three critical contexts:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-ebms-partition.md:36
msgid "<b> Probability Evaluation</b>"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-ebms-partition.md:38
#, python-brace-format
msgid ""
"To compute the probability $P_\\theta(\\mathbf{x})$ of a specific "
"configuration, we must divide the Boltzmann factor by $Z_\\theta$:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-ebms-partition.md:40
msgid "P_\\theta(\\mathbf{x}) = \\frac{\\exp(-E_\\theta(\\mathbf{x}))}{Z_\\theta}"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-ebms-partition.md:42
msgid ""
"Without $Z_\\theta$, we have only an unnormalized score. This means we "
"cannot directly compute likelihoods on test data, making model comparison"
" and hyperparameter tuning difficult."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-ebms-partition.md:44
msgid "<b>Learning by Gradient Descent</b>"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-ebms-partition.md:46
msgid ""
"Recall from Section [3.1 Defining the Objective: Low Energy for Real Data"
"](/kpp-theoretical-foundations\\kpp-theoretical-foundations-ebms-def) "
"that the gradient of the negative log-likelihood decomposes into a data "
"term and a model term:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-ebms-partition.md:48
msgid ""
"\\nabla f(\\theta) = -\\mathbb{E}_{\\text{data}} \\left[ \\frac{\\partial"
" E_\\theta}{\\partial \\theta} \\right] + \\mathbb{E}_{\\text{model}} "
"\\left[ \\frac{\\partial E_\\theta}{\\partial \\theta} \\right]"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-ebms-partition.md:50
msgid ""
"Note: $\\nabla f(\\theta) = -\\frac{\\partial \\mathcal{L}}{\\partial "
"\\theta}$, where $\\mathcal{L}$ is the negative log-likelihood minimized "
"in many textbooks."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-ebms-partition.md:52
msgid ""
"The first term is straightforward to estimate from the training set. The "
"second term, i.e. the expectation under the model distribution "
"$P_\\theta$, is the source of difficulty. As shown in the expression "
"above, computing this expectation exactly requires summing over all $2^N$"
" possible configurations, weighted by the Boltzmann factor. Both the "
"numerator and the denominator involve the partition function $Z_\\theta$,"
" making exact gradient evaluation computationally intractable for any "
"non-trivial model."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-ebms-partition.md:54
msgid ""
"The <b>model expectation </b>$\\mathbb{E}_{\\text{model}}[\\cdot]$<em> is"
" an average over the model distribution </em>$P_\\theta$:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-ebms-partition.md:56
msgid ""
"\\mathbb{E}_{\\text{model}} \\left[ \\frac{\\partial E_\\theta}{\\partial"
" \\theta} \\right] = \\sum_{\\tilde{\\mathbf{x}}} "
"P_\\theta(\\tilde{\\mathbf{x}}) \\frac{\\partial "
"E_\\theta(\\tilde{\\mathbf{x}})}{\\partial \\theta} = "
"\\frac{1}{Z_\\theta} \\sum_{\\tilde{\\mathbf{x}}} "
"\\exp(-E_\\theta(\\tilde{\\mathbf{x}})) \\frac{\\partial "
"E_\\theta(\\tilde{\\mathbf{x}})}{\\partial \\theta}"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-ebms-partition.md:58
msgid ""
"Both the numerator and the denominator involve sums over all $2^N$ "
"configurations. Exact gradient computation is infeasible."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-ebms-partition.md:60
msgid "<b>Sampling and Inference</b>"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-ebms-partition.md:62
msgid ""
"Generating samples from the model distribution typically requires Markov "
"chain Monte Carlo (MCMC) methods, such as Gibbs sampling. While MCMC does"
" not require computing $Z_\\theta$ explicitly, it does require running "
"the Markov chain long enough to reach equilibrium. The time required to "
"obtain independent samples scales with the <b>mixing time</b> of the "
"chain, which can be exponentially long in the system size, especially "
"when the energy landscape has high barriers."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-ebms-partition.md:64
msgid "<b>The Partition Function as a Free Energy Barrier</b>"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-ebms-partition.md:66
msgid ""
"In statistical physics, the partition function is intimately related to "
"the <b>Helmholtz free energy</b> $F$:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-ebms-partition.md:68
msgid "F = -\\log Z"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-ebms-partition.md:70
#, python-brace-format
msgid ""
"(Setting $ k_B T = 1$ for notational simplicity.) The free energy "
"summarizes the balance between energy and entropy. For a given visible "
"configuration $\\mathbf{v}$ in a Boltzmann machine with hidden units "
"$\\mathbf{h}$, the <b>free energy</b> is defined analogously:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-ebms-partition.md:72
msgid ""
"F_\\theta(\\mathbf{v}) = -\\log \\sum_{\\tilde{\\mathbf{h}}} "
"\\exp\\left(-E_\\theta(\\mathbf{v}, \\tilde{\\mathbf{h}})\\right)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-ebms-partition.md:74
msgid "The probability of a visible vector is then:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-ebms-partition.md:76
msgid ""
"P_\\theta(\\mathbf{v}) = "
"\\frac{\\exp(-F_\\theta(\\mathbf{v}))}{\\sum_{\\tilde{\\mathbf{v}}} "
"\\exp(-F_\\theta(\\tilde{\\mathbf{v}}))}"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-ebms-partition.md:78
msgid ""
"Even with hidden units marginalized out, the denominator still sums over "
"all $2^{N_{\\text{vis}}}$ visible configurations. The intractability "
"remains."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-ebms-partition.md:80
msgid "<b>The Consequence: Exact Maximum Likelihood Is Impossible</b>"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-ebms-partition.md:82
msgid ""
"The intractability of $Z_\\theta$ has a stark implication: <b>exact "
"maximum likelihood learning of a Boltzmann machine is computationally "
"impossible for all but the smallest toy problems.</b> Any practical "
"training algorithm must rely on approximations."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-ebms-partition.md:84
msgid ""
"This is not merely an engineering inconvenience; it is a fundamental "
"computational barrier. The partition function sum is a prototypical "
"#P-complete problem in computational complexity theory, meaning it is at "
"least as hard as counting the number of satisfying assignments to a "
"Boolean formula."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-ebms-partition.md:86
msgid "Hessian and Non-Convexity"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-ebms-partition.md:88
msgid ""
"The difficulty extends beyond the gradient. The Hessian of the log-"
"likelihood function also reveals the complexity of the optimization "
"landscape. For a Boltzmann machine with only visible units, the Hessian "
"has a simple and revealing form:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-ebms-partition.md:90
#, python-brace-format
msgid "\\nabla^2 f(\\theta) = -\\text{Cov}_\\theta(\\mathbf{S})"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-ebms-partition.md:92
#, python-brace-format
msgid ""
"where $\\mathbf{S}$ is the vector of sufficient statistics (e.g., $X_i$ "
"and $X_i X_j$). This means the Hessian is negative definite, and the "
"optimization is <b>concave</b>—there are no non-global local minima when "
"all units are visible."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-ebms-partition.md:94
msgid "However, when hidden units are introduced, the Hessian becomes:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-ebms-partition.md:96
msgid ""
"\\nabla^2 f(\\theta) = "
"\\mathbb{E}_{\\text{target}}[\\text{Cov}_\\theta(\\mathbf{S}|\\mathbf{X})]"
" - \\text{Cov}_\\theta(\\mathbf{S})"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-ebms-partition.md:98
msgid ""
"The first term is the conditional covariance given the visible units, and"
" the second term is the unconditional covariance under the model. This "
"expression is <b>not</b> necessarily negative semidefinite, meaning that "
"<b>the log-likelihood is not concave</b> in the presence of hidden units."
" Consequently, gradient-based methods can converge to local optima, and "
"the quality of the learned model depends crucially on the initialization "
"and optimization algorithm."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-ebms-partition.md:100
msgid "<b>Approaches to Taming the Intractability</b>"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-ebms-partition.md:102
msgid ""
"Faced with this barrier, researchers have developed several families of "
"approximation strategies. Understanding these strategies is essential for"
" navigating the landscape of energy-based learning."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-ebms-partition.md:104
msgid "<b>Sampling-Based Approximations</b>"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-ebms-partition.md:106
msgid ""
"Instead of summing over all configurations, we can <b>sample "
"</b>configurations from the model distribution using MCMC. The model "
"expectation is then approximated by an empirical average over the "
"samples:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-ebms-partition.md:108
msgid ""
"\\mathbb{E}_{\\text{model}} \\left[ \\frac{\\partial E_\\theta}{\\partial"
" \\theta} \\right] \\approx \\frac{1}{K} \\sum_{k=1}^K \\frac{\\partial "
"E_\\theta(\\tilde{\\mathbf{x}}^{(k)})}{\\partial \\theta}, \\quad "
"\\tilde{\\mathbf{x}}^{(k)} \\sim P_\\theta"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-ebms-partition.md:110
msgid ""
"The challenge is that obtaining unbiased samples requires running the "
"Markov chain to equilibrium for every gradient step, which is "
"prohibitively slow. <b>Contrastive divergence</b> (Section [3.3 "
"Contrastive Divergence](/kpp-theoretical-foundations\\kpp-theoretical-"
"foundations-ebms-cd)) and <b>persistent contrastive divergence</b> "
"address this by using short MCMC runs initialized from the data or from "
"previous model states."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-ebms-partition.md:112
msgid "<b>Variational Approximations</b>"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-ebms-partition.md:114
msgid ""
"Variational methods replace the intractable model distribution "
"$P_\\theta$ with a simpler, tractable <b>variational distribution</b> "
"$Q_\\phi$ from a restricted family. The parameters $ \\phi$ are optimized"
" to make $Q_\\phi$ as close as possible to $P_\\theta$ in the sense of "
"Kullback-Leibler divergence. This transforms the learning problem into an"
" optimization over both $ \\theta$ and $\\phi$."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-ebms-partition.md:116
msgid ""
"While variational methods provide a rigorous lower bound on the log-"
"likelihood, they often require making strong independence assumptions "
"(e.g., mean-field approximations) that can limit the model's expressive "
"power."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-ebms-partition.md:118
msgid "<b>Architectural Constraints</b>"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-ebms-partition.md:120
#, python-brace-format
msgid ""
"By restricting the connectivity pattern of the Boltzmann machine, we can "
"make certain computations tractable. The <b>Restricted Boltzmann Machine "
"(RBM)</b> is the most celebrated example. By eliminating visible-visible "
"and hidden-hidden connections, the conditional distributions "
"$P(\\mathbf{h} \\mid \\mathbf{v})$ and $P(\\mathbf{v} \\mid \\mathbf{h})$"
" factorize into products of independent Bernoulli distributions. This "
"allows efficient Gibbs sampling and enables the contrastive divergence "
"algorithm."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-ebms-partition.md:122
msgid "<b>Score Matching and Noise Contrastive Estimation</b>"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-ebms-partition.md:124
msgid ""
"These are alternative training criteria that circumvent the partition "
"function entirely. <b>Score matching</b> minimizes the Fisher divergence "
"between the model and data distributions by matching the gradients of "
"their log-densities, which does not require $Z_\\theta$. <b>Noise "
"contrastive estimation (NCE)</b> transforms the unsupervised learning "
"problem into a supervised logistic regression task of distinguishing data"
" samples from noise samples, where the partition function becomes a "
"learnable parameter."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-ebms-partition.md:126
msgid "<b>Annealed Importance Sampling</b>"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-ebms-partition.md:128
msgid ""
"For model evaluation (rather than training), <b>annealed importance "
"sampling (AIS)</b> provides an unbiased estimate of $Z_\\theta$. It works"
" by gradually transforming a simple base distribution (e.g., uniform) "
"into the model distribution through a sequence of intermediate "
"distributions, using importance weights to correct for the sampling bias."
" While computationally expensive, AIS is a gold standard for evaluating "
"generative models when exact likelihoods are required."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-ebms-partition.md:130
msgid "<b>The Partition Function in the Era of Deep Learning</b>"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-ebms-partition.md:132
msgid ""
"It is worth noting that the intractability of the partition function is "
"not unique to Boltzmann machines. Many modern deep generative models face"
" analogous challenges:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-ebms-partition.md:134
msgid ""
"<b>Generative Adversarial Networks (GANs)</b> avoid the partition "
"function entirely by using an adversarial training criterion that does "
"not require likelihood evaluation."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-ebms-partition.md:135
msgid ""
"<b>Variational Autoencoders (VAEs)</b> use a variational lower bound that"
" circumvents the partition function."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-ebms-partition.md:136
msgid ""
"<b>Normalizing Flows</b> design architectures where the Jacobian "
"determinant, the analog of $Z_\\theta$, is tractable by construction."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-ebms-partition.md:137
msgid ""
"<b>Diffusion Models</b> learn to reverse a gradual noising process, with "
"a training objective that involves only tractable conditional "
"distributions."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-ebms-partition.md:139
msgid ""
"The Boltzmann machine's struggle with the partition function thus "
"foreshadows a central theme in deep generative modeling: the tension "
"between expressive power and tractable normalization."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-ebms-partition.md:141
msgid "<b>Summary</b>"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-ebms-partition.md:143
msgid ""
"The <b>partition function</b> $Z_\\theta = \\sum_{\\mathbf{x}} "
"\\exp(-E_\\theta(\\mathbf{x}))$ is a sum over an exponential number of "
"configurations, making exact computation infeasible for non-trivial "
"models."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-ebms-partition.md:144
msgid ""
"The intractability of $Z_\\theta$ prevents exact <b>probability "
"evaluation</b>, exact <b>gradient computation</b>, and efficient exact "
"<b>sampling</b>."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-ebms-partition.md:145
msgid ""
"This computational barrier implies that <b>exact maximum likelihood "
"learning is impossible</b> for general Boltzmann machines."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-ebms-partition.md:146
msgid ""
"Approximation strategies fall into several categories: <b>sampling-"
"based</b> (MCMC, contrastive divergence), <b>variational</b> (mean-"
"field), <b>architectural constraints</b> (RBM), and <b>alternative "
"objectives</b> (score matching, NCE)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-ebms-partition.md:147
msgid ""
"The partition function problem is a fundamental challenge that connects "
"Boltzmann machines to contemporary deep generative models, many of which "
"are designed explicitly to circumvent or tame this intractability."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-ebms-partition.md:148
msgid ""
"The <b>Restricted Boltzmann Machine</b> and <b>contrastive divergence, "
"</b>topics of the upcoming sections, provide a pragmatic and influential "
"solution to this problem for a restricted but powerful class of "
"architectures."
msgstr ""

